  1. This following codes build a predictive model to predict if a passenger in the titanic is survived or not. A common practice is to split the data into 2 subdata: a train data and a test data. The model is build from the train data and then tested on the test data.

# Split the data into 70% training and 30% testing
library(caret)
## Loading required package: lattice
## 
## Attaching package: 'caret'
## The following object is masked from 'package:purrr':
## 
##     lift
splitIndex <- createDataPartition(titanic$target, p = .70, list = FALSE)
train <- titanic[ splitIndex,]
test <- titanic[-splitIndex,]

library(rpart) #load the rpart package

# build a tree
mytree <- rpart(target ~ ., data = train, method = "class")

# Plot the tree
library(rattle)
## Rattle: A free graphical interface for data science with R.
## Version 5.2.0 Copyright (c) 2006-2018 Togaware Pty Ltd.
## Type 'rattle()' to shake, rattle, and roll your data.
fancyRpartPlot(mytree)

# Evaluate the tree on the testing data

#predict on testing data
pred <- predict(mytree,test, type = "class")

#Evaluate the predictions

cm=confusionMatrix(data = pred, reference = factor(test$target), positive = "1")

Parameter tuning is the process to find out the best selection for the parameter. What would be the best selection of the parameter maxdepth?

#The third decision tree is the most accurate so I would go with that one
  1. A random forest is a combination of many trees. The decision of random forest is a majority vote between all the trees. For example, if a forest has 5 trees and three (majority) trees predict a passenger survived, the forest also predict that passenger survived. If only two trees predict survived, the forest would predict the passenger not survived.
# Building random forest using ranger

# import the ranger library
library(ranger)
## 
## Attaching package: 'ranger'
## The following object is masked from 'package:rattle':
## 
##     importance
#train a forest of 10 trees and consider a random of 3 variables at each split
model = ranger(target ~., data = train, mtry = 1, num.trees = 10)

# predict and test on the test dataset
pred3  = predict(model, data = test)$predictions

# Get the confusion matrix
confusionMatrix(pred3, factor(test$target), positive="1")

Compute the training errors of random forest with mtry running from 1 to its maximum and num.trees running from 1 to 20.

df <- data.frame()
for (num in 1:20) {
for (value in 1:8) {
  mod= ranger(target ~., data = train, mtry = value, num.trees = num)
  pred3=predict(model, data = train)$predictions
data_frame=data.frame("mtry"=num,"num.trees"=value,"Accuracy"=confusionMatrix(factor(pred3),factor(train$target),positive="1")$overall["Accuracy"])
df<-rbind(df,data_frame)
}  }

df<- df %>%
  select(c(num.trees,mtry,Accuracy)) %>%

Compute the testing errors of random forest with mtry running from 1 to its maximum and num.trees running from 1 to 20.

df <- data.frame()
for (num in 1:20) {
for (value in 1:8) {
  mod= ranger(target ~., data = test, mtry = value, num.trees = num)
  pred3=predict(model, data = test)$predictions
data_frame=data.frame("mtry"=num,"num.trees"=value,"Accuracy"=confusionMatrix(factor(pred3),factor(test$target),positive="1")$overall["Accuracy"])
df<-rbind(df,data_frame)
}  }

df<- df %>%
  select(c(num.trees,mtry,Accuracy)) %>%
  arrange (-Accuracy)

Random Forest on the Adult data

df<-data.frame()
x<-c(2:6)
y<-c(4:8)
for (i in x) {
  for (j in y){
#train a forest of 10 trees and consider a random of 3 variables at each split
model = ranger(target ~., data = train, mtry = i, num.trees = j, splitrule = "gini")

# predict and test on the test dataset
pred3  = predict(model, data = test)$predictions

# Get the confusion matrix
cm<-confusionMatrix(pred3, factor(test$target), positive="1")

data_frame=data.frame("mtry"=i,"num.trees"=j,"Accuracy"=confusionMatrix(factor(pred3),factor(test$target),positive="1")$overall["Accuracy"])
df<-rbind(df,data_frame)
}  }

  select(c(num.trees,mtry,Accuracy)) %>%
  arrange (-Accuracy)
